Cell.Text: Reasons? Since when does a man need a reason to protect his family, to defend his homeland? | It's the damn outlanders and Empire that need the reasons.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsGalmar: What are your reasons for joining the war?

Cell.Text: Enough talk. There's much to do.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsGalmarNevermind: Never mind.

Cell.Text: Not this Empire. The world's better without it. Certainly Skyrim is. | I fought in the Imperial army in the War against the Dominion. I bled and spilt blood for the Empire. And for what? | The Empire to bend it's knee before those evil elf bastards? Signing a treaty meant to kill the heart of the Empire itself. To deny Talos? | No. I'll have no part of any such Empire. And I'll gladly gut anyone who says otherwise.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsGalmarEmpire: Hasn't Skyrim always been part of the Empire?

Cell.Text: [E] I oppose tyranny. I oppose those who tell me how to live, what to think, and what to believe. | I'm a man. Skyrim is man's homeland. That's a fact. A fact I'm proud of. There's no shame in that. Read you history.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsGalmarOutlanders: Do you oppose anyone who's not a Nord?

Cell.Text: I am a loyal citizen of the Empire. My parents were Legionnaires, and I've followed in their footsteps. | But more importantly, I am a daughter of Skyrim and wish to see her made whole again.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsRikke: Why do you fight for the Empire?

Cell.Text: I've been a daughter of Skyrim all my life. I love this land and her people. So do all the Nords that serve the Empire. | Ulfric, too, once. He wasn't always a self-serving ego-maniac. He fought in the Imperial army in the War against the Dominion. | But Ulfric and his "Stormcloaks" are deluding themselves. If there's any hope of a long term victory against the Dominion, it's in the Empire. | The rebels are only inflaming the tension and weakening the Empire by distracting it from it's ultimate aim.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsRikkeDaughter: Don't Stormcloaks call themselves "sons and daughters of Skyrim"?

Cell.Text: If that's all, there's pressing concerns that need dealing with.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsRikkeNevermind: Never mind.

Cell.Text: G|I consider this conversation over.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsRikkeThalmor: Do you consider the Thalmor enemies?

Cell.Text: I'm a soldier, not a politician. And my personal beliefs are not yours to question.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsRikkeTalos: So you have no problem with the treaty that bans the worship of Talos?

Cell.Text: My parents were traveling merchants eventually settling in Cyrodiil. I must have inherited their wanderlust... | I joined the Legion to see the world. I know, that's one of those things people say, but it's completely true in my case. | Wasn't long before I saw more of the world than I bargained for.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsFieldCO: Why did you join the Legion?

Cell.Text: You're from Cyrodiil? What's it like back home?

Home? Home to me is a hot cup of ale at the end of the day and five minutes without someone needing something from me... | Cyrodiil is a beautiful place, full of diverse peoples and histories. But so too, Hammerfell and Skyrim, and every other place I've been. | Don't get me wrong, every country has it's dark corners. But that's why we're here. To bring order and civilization, and to protect the people.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsFieldCOFollowup1: Please continue...

Cell.Text: Sounds like you've seen you far share of hardship.

The life of a soldier is full of hardship. That's nothing. | But they send the Legion to places that've gotten too bad to be settled without violence. What's hard is seeing good people warped by evil. | And I've seen the face of evil. It was in the air above Sentinel on the Night of Green Fire.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsFieldCOFollowup2: You mentioned something back there...

Cell.Text: For the glory of the Empire.

Node.Caption: CWReasonsFieldCODone: That's all I wanted to know.

Cell.Text: Not everyone seems to want us here.

Ulfric and his thugs are stirring up trouble for their own agenda. The Empire is the only thing keeping the Dominion from walking all over Skyrim. | It matters little if some of the people here are ignorant to that truth. They are still citizens of the Empire. It's our solemn duty to protect them.

Node.Caption: CWFieldCOFollowUp1B: Go on...

Cell.Text: What happened during the Night of Green Fire?

Back in 42 I was stationed in Hammerfell, on leave in Sentinel, trying to track down some refugee relatives who had fled persecution in Alinor. | Suddenly an explosion of magic in the refugee quarter. Thalmor mages were attacking the Altmer dissidents who were resisting with magic of their own. | I ran to the scene with other Legionaries who where stationed there, but the entire quarter was a smoking ruin by the time we arrived. | Everyone was dead. Wholesale slaughter. The Dominion, not content with killing dissidents at home, came to Hammerfell to finish the job. | We're supposedly at peace now. But I put in to be stationed here to keep an eye on the Thalmor. I've a feeling they're behind this unrest in Skyrim.

Node.Caption: CWFieldCOFollowup2B: I'm listening...

Cell.Text: Ulfric Stromcloak's head rolling away from his lifeless body.

I hope Ulfric will come to his senses. But I fear he's in too far to stop now. | Likely only Ulfric's death, or the overthrow of the Jarls supporting him will end this. Either way, much blood will be spilt.
What is the aim of this war?

First we'll kick the Thalmor and their bloody Imperial puppets out of the country. Then we'll rebuild Skyrim into the land she once was. | When we're done with that, we'll take our army to the Dominion, and show those pointy-eared bastards not every man is fit to be their slave.
Why are you fighting this war?

We're fighting because we're done bleeding for an Empire that won't bleed for us. | Untold numbers of Nords died defending the Empire against the Dominion. And for what? | Skyrim being sold to the Thalmor so the Emperor could keep his throne! | We're fighting because our own Jarls, once strong, wise men, have become fearful and blind to their people's suffering. | We're fighting because Skyrim needs heroes, and there's no one else but us.

Node.Caption: CWWhatWillItTakeTopic: What will it take to end the war?

Cell.Text: I killed Torygg to prove our wretched condition. How is the High King supposed to be the defender of Skyrim, if he can't even defend himself?

Node.Caption: CWHighKingTopic: Why did you kill the High King?

Cell.Text: I challenged him in the traditional way, and he accepted. There were many witnesses. No "murder" was committed. | True, he didn't stand a chance against me. | But that was precisely the point! He was a puppet-king of the Empire , not a High King of Skyrim. | His father before him perhaps, but not Torygg. | He was too privileged and too foolish, more interested in entertaining his queen than ruling his country.

Node.Caption: CWHighKingMurder: Some call you a murderer.

Cell.Text: There hasn't been a true High King in Skyrim for generations. | For too long he's been hand picked by the Emperor, and given emphatic nods by milk-drinking Jarls addicted to Imperial coin. | It's time we had a real High King. One of our own making.

Node.Caption: CWHighKingYou: Do you desire to be the High King?

Cell.Text: Indeed, Elisif has become Jarl of Solitude, historically and conveniently home of the High King, backed by Imperial interests. | But the Moot has not yet met to name her High Queen. And they won't. Not as long as I have any say in it.

Node.Caption: CWHighKingElisif: And what of his widow? Doesn't she claim the throne?

Cell.Text: My father, the great Bear of Eastmarch, died during my imprisonment after the Markarth Incident. | I, his only son, forced to deliver his eulogy via a letter I had smuggled out of prison. Such is the love of Titus Mede for his subjects. | When finally set free, I returned to Windhelm, and was greeted by a city in mourning, at one with my own grief and anger. | Clamoring in angry voices, calling out for justice, for war, they sat me on the throne. | The Throne of Ysgramor! The throne of my father... I only hope I can prove worthy of the honor.

Node.Caption: CWJarlOfWindhelmTopic: How did you become the Jarl of Eastmarch?

Cell.Text: G|I'm originally from Cyrodiil, sent here at the request of the Emperor himself. I'm often ordered to places with problems that need fixing. | Now, while I'm certain this is all terribly interesting to you, I have important matters to attend.

Node.Caption: CWAboutYourselfTopic: Have you always lived in Skyrim?

Cell.Text: The Legion's always been here. Without us to keep order, the provinces would fall into barbarism and lawlessness. Especially Skyrim. | Take for example, Ulfric Stormcloak and his little "rebellion." But rest assured, his days are numbered.

Node.Caption: CWWhatsEmpireDoingTopic: What's the Imperial Legion doing in Skyrim?

Cell.Text: Not entirely true, though not entirely false either. | Any Nord can learn the Way of the Voice by studying with the Greybeards, given enough ambition and dedication. | My shouting Torygg to the ground proved he had neither. | However, it was my sword piercing his heart that killed him.

Node.Caption: CWShoutTopic: At Helgen, they said you shouted the King to death?
